How can refs help with handling user inputs in forms?

Refs are used when you want to reference a value but you don't need it for rendering.  Refs don't trigger
a rerender and don't depend on rendering to work.

In a form, when you track state, every keystroke can cause a rerender (change in state).  With a reference you are able to capture a value at a specific time (for ex after a submit event).



What is an uncontrolled component? What is a controlled component?
Who is managing the value in an input element?  The programmer (controlled) or are you allowing the default
behavior of the browser to occur (uncontrolled)?

When should you not use refs?
You shouldn't use refs when you want to update the UI.
If you want validation, live feedback or character counts on an input form, use state, not refs.

What's the main idea behind portals?
Portals are a built in method that are used to allow DOM elements to escape their parent container, for example
if you need to use a modal, or a pop up, or an ad that needs to be on a different level than the other HTML 
(z-index is a good example.)  I like to think of it as stacking papers.  The bottom page is your main HTML and
you can use a portal to add another page (or layer on top).